Occasional Under the Leg Throw In Cascad.explanation:
throw under the leg, lift your leg up into your pattern, and move an object you're holding under your leg before you throw it. You don't have to reach or bend down and throw from an unusually low position, just bring your leg up high enough that you can easily put your hand under it while juggling.
The most common way to throw under the leg is throwing under the same leg: if you're using your right hand, you throw under your right leg. You can also throw under the opposite leg (e.g. throwing with the right hand under the left leg). If you squat down or jump, it's possible to throw an object under both legs at the same time.

Normally if the right hand throws under either leg, it moves under the leg from right to left, and then throws on the left side of the leg. A more difficult variation is to move your hand under your leg in the opposite direction: move your right hand under either leg from left to right, and throw from the right side of your leg.

An under the leg catch is an under the leg throw in reverse: you lift your leg up into the pattern, reach under your leg with an empty hand, and catch an object in this position.
Occasional Under the Leg Throw In Cascad.name: Occasional Under the Leg Throw In Cascade

Partner Cascade (Siamese Juggling).explanation:
Both partners should know how to juggle 3 balls
1. Stand side by side.
2. One person puts 2 balls in their right hand and the other person
 puts one ball in their left hand.
3. The person with 2 balls starts.
 The starter says something like 1, 2, 3, Go and throws up ball #1.
4. The other person waits for ball #1 to be up in the air, then
 throws ball #2 up and under ball #1. 5. When ball #2 in the air, the starter throws ball #3 up and under ball #2.  Each person takes turns throwing and then you're juggling together.

Top of the Head Stall(1b).explanation:
Start off with a beanbag on your head and one in each hand. Throw the beanbag from your right hand.

As soon as the right hand has thrown the beanbag, it reaches up and grabs the one on top of your head. Keep looking at the one in the air.

Throw the beanbag from the left hand so that you can catch the first beanbag in the same hand. From this point onwards it's just like normal juggling.

The right hand throws it's beanbag and catches the one coming down.

The left hand throws its beanbag and catches the one coming down. Wait for it! The tricky part comes next...

As the right hand throws its beanbag to catch another, the left places its beanbag back on your head.

Catch the final beanbag in your left hand and - phew - that's it! A long description, but it doesn't take very long. Try to do it again, but start by taking the beanbag with the left hand this time. Go on, it's easy!
